title: Cape Cod
text: Cape Cod is a common architectural style of home in suburban communities. These story-and-a-half homes include dormers and feature symmetrical windows with a central doorway. Common characteristics of capes include shingle siding, shutters, simple exterior decoration, and sometimes, a small roof overhang.

title: Victorian
text: Victorian architecture refers to an era of design instead of one specific style. Victorian-style houses feature a steeply pitched roof, ornate gables, turrets, painted iron railings, octagonal or round towers to draw the eye upward, and sliding sash and canted bay windows that were often stained glass.

title: Colonial
text: Colonial-style homes date back to the 17th century and come in many variations. The homes are typically rectangular and feature symmetry and some type of dormer. Common features of Colonials include a gabled, triangular roof with sloping sides, window grids or mullions, shutters, double chimneys, and a brick façade.

title: Craftsman
text: The American Craftsman-style home came about in the early 20th century during the Arts and Crafts movement. These homes focus on materials and motifs inspired by nature, especially on the interior. You’ll commonly find naturally toned woodwork, geometric stained glass, and several built-ins. The color palette of a Craftsman-style home looks and feels earthy and includes forest green, rusty orange, and natural browns.

title: Prairie
text: Prairie-style homes are inspired by their relationship to nature. They feature handcrafted details like simple woodwork, stained glass, and built-in furniture.Prairie-style architecture did not flourish beyond the Midwest. Frank Lloyd Wright intended the architecture to mimic the horizontal lines of the region but the designs didn't appeal to the masses across the country and quickly faded away around 1915.1 However, the style is still an iconic example of architecture that originated in America.

title: Ranch
text: Ranch homes are single-story or split-level houses that started popping up across the U.S. during the first half of the 20th century. They have open floor plans, large windows towards the front of the house, are rectangular or L shaped, have a low-pitched roofline, and often have designated deck or patio space in the backyard.

title: Tudor
text: Tudor-style homes are easily recognizable thanks to their timber details against a light-colored stucco. The Tudor style came from historical homes in England. This home style became popular during the early 20th century in wealthy suburban communities across the U.S. Many Tudor homes can be found in northern climates because the solid architecture is ideal for cold weather.

title: Mediterranean
text: Mediterranean-style homes often feature warm tones, stucco exteriors, and beautiful ornamental details incorporated into the tile and woodwork. The homes are made to be open and airy with stone, wood beams, and other natural details.It became popular in the warmer parts of the U.S. during the early 1900s. Tuscan-style architecture differs from the Mediterranean style although they look similar. Tuscan styles come specifically from Italy and Mediterranean styles originate from Spanish, Greek, and Moroccan regions.

title: Modern
text: Modern home design is inspired by the modernism movement that emerged in the 1930s, emphasizing clean, sharp, functional design, modern materials such as concrete, steel, and glass, minimal ornamentation, neutral palettes, and open plans. These homes are found across the country with many on the West Coast.

title: Contemporary
text: Contemporary architecture essentially refers to the building styles that are trendy in the present. They vary greatly, but these houses generally connect the indoors and the outdoors to convey a sense of flow and natural light. The design of these homes emphasizes sustainability and energy efficiency, as well.

title: Farmhouse
text: A farmhouse-style house is a modern interpretation of the rural family farm homes situated on lots of acreage. They came in various design styles, including Victorian and Colonial, but the most common farmhouse was a simple rectangular structure often with a long porch and a clapboard exterior. Covered porches and exposed beams are also common in this style of home.

title: Cottage
text: Cottages are defined by their small size and are usually faced with stone or wood, though siding has become common. They are typically one to one-and-a-half stories high and often have small porches. The interior is cozy and informal. Modest cottage-style homes originated in Europe in small towns and villages. And they now dot the U.S., especially in quaint residential communities.

title: Cabin
text: Cabins are known for being warm and cozy. The exterior is often formed with logs, or it is at least clad in wood as a nod to the original style. The shape is simple, usually with a fairly open interior with decorative nods to nature and wilderness

title: Rowhouse
text: Rowhouses, also known as townhouses, are homes built directly next to one another with an adjoining wall. This type of house is common in major cities throughout the country, where the lot sizes are long and narrow. Often the same architect will build most, if not all, of the rowhouses on a block, giving them a uniform look. The design style can vary depending on the architect's preferences.

title: Greek Revival
text: Greek Revival architecture is inspired by buildings from ancient Greece and defined by large columns, symmetrical shapes, and white façades.The style first arrived in Britain during the 1700s, but it didn't gain steam until the 19th century in the U.S. As a new democracy, Americans wanted to pay tribute to the birthplace of democracy through architecture, which is why many government buildings use the style. Home examples now can be found across the country.

title: French Country
text: French country homes draw inspiration from centuries-old homes in the French countryside. These homes featured more natural and lived-in elements than the ornate French architecture that dominated cities. Some key features of French country homes include natural stone facades, a sloping roof, two chimneys, and natural wood or stone flooring. Such homes can be found scattered in residential communities across the U.S.

title: Saltbox
text: A saltbox home features a slanted, asymmetrical roof and a large chimney. The front of the house is flat, and there are typically two stories in the front sloping down to just one in the back.Saltbox houses first popped up in New England during the 1600s, and they’re still most common there today. They were simple structures that early settlers built with the supplies they could get their hands on, namely local timber.

title: Art Deco
text: On the exterior, Art Deco was extremely popular in commercial buildings and as public monuments, however, the interior design was something to be desired in residences. Trademarks of the Art Deco style include ornate and geometric details, bold colors, decorative windows and doors, and parapets and spires.

title: Gothic Revival
text: Trademark elements of the Gothic Revival style include pointed arches, stained glass windows, and ornate features such as spires and gargoyles. It’s not common to see a home fully in the style, though residences will have aspects of it.Originating in France and defined by pointed arches, Gothic architecture was popular in Europe from the 12th century to the 16th century. Gothic Revival arose in the 19th century. Many buildings in the U.S., especially cathedrals, feature the Gothic Revival style.

title: Midcentury Modern
text: Midcentury modern architecture and interior decor are well-known for clean lines, little ornamentation, and a distinct connection with nature bringing the outdoors indoors. Characteristics include large, open floorplans, and floor-to-ceiling picture windows. These homes are often one story.This classic style of architecture and interior design that harkens back to a simpler, more optimistic time has experienced a major resurgence in recent years.
